# 🔍 Troubleshooting Notes

This document covers common issues encountered when setting up and managing the AWS EC2 instance, SSH connections, Apache web server, and networking configuration for this project.

---

## SSH Connection Issues

### 1. Permission Denied (publickey)

**Symptoms:**  
Permission denied (publickey,gssapi-keyex,gssapi-with-mic).

markdown
Copy
Edit

**Causes & Fixes:**  
- **Wrong key path or filename:** Verify the path to your `.pem` file is correct and accessible.  
  ```bash
  ls -l /c/Users/YourUser/Downloads/my-key.pem
Key permissions too open: SSH requires the private key to have restrictive permissions.

bash
Copy
Edit
chmod 400 /path/to/my-key.pem
Key not associated with EC2 instance: Ensure the EC2 instance was launched with the correct key pair (my-key).

Wrong username: For Amazon Linux 2 or AL2023 AMIs, use ec2-user. For Ubuntu AMIs, use ubuntu.
Example:

bash
Copy
Edit
ssh -i /path/to/my-key.pem ec2-user@3.140.197.242
Check SSH verbose output: Use -v to debug connection issues.

bash
Copy
Edit
ssh -i /path/to/my-key.pem ec2-user@3.140.197.242 -v
Apache Web Server Issues
1. Apache Not Starting
Symptoms:

sudo systemctl status apache2 or httpd shows inactive or failed.

Fixes:

Check service status and logs:

bash
Copy
Edit
sudo systemctl status httpd
sudo journalctl -xe
Make sure no other service is using port 80:

bash
Copy
Edit
sudo lsof -i :80
Install Apache properly:

bash
Copy
Edit
sudo yum install httpd -y  # Amazon Linux / AL2023
sudo apt install apache2 -y  # Ubuntu
Enable and start service:

bash
Copy
Edit
sudo systemctl enable httpd
sudo systemctl start httpd
2. Webpage Not Loading
Check AWS Security Group allows inbound on port 80 (HTTP).

Verify Apache root directory has your index.html and correct permissions.

Test with curl from inside the instance:

bash
Copy
Edit
curl http://localhost
Network & Security Group Troubleshooting
1. Cannot Connect to EC2 on Port 22 (SSH)
Verify security group attached to EC2 allows inbound TCP on port 22 from your IP.

Check local firewall settings on your machine.

2. HTTP/HTTPS Access Issues
Security group must allow inbound TCP on ports 80 and/or 443.

Check Network ACLs in your VPC to ensure traffic is not blocked.

File Permissions and Ownership
Private key .pem files must be restricted:

bash
Copy
Edit
chmod 400 my-key.pem
Apache document root files should be readable by Apache user (apache or www-data).

Common Commands Reference
bash
Copy
Edit
# Connect with SSH verbose mode
ssh -i /path/to/my-key.pem ec2-user@3.140.197.242 -v

# Change key file permission
chmod 400 /path/to/my-key.pem

# Start Apache service
sudo systemctl start httpd

# Enable Apache service to start on boot
sudo systemctl enable httpd

# Check Apache status
sudo systemctl status httpd

# Check open port 80 connections
sudo lsof -i :80

# View system logs for errors
sudo journalctl -xe
Additional Tips
Double-check the username for your EC2 AMI type (ec2-user, ubuntu, admin, etc.).

Ensure your .pem file matches the key pair selected during instance launch.

Use Elastic IPs if you want a persistent public IP instead of the auto-assigned IP that changes on reboot.

IMDSv2 enabled on your instance requires updated tooling or settings for metadata queries.

Keep this document updated with new issues and solutions as you work through the project.

